The Technical Reality: SAP HANA and ETL
In systems like SAP HANA, the ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) process is rigid and uncompromising:

Validation: Before the data ever hits the high-speed in-memory database, it is validated against a Schema. If the JSON payload contains corrupt data, unexpected fields, or "malicious" strings, the system rejects it or pushes it to an "Error/Exception" queue.

Transformation Logic: Before the data is "Loaded," it undergoes complex mapping. It is normalized, cleaned, and sanitized. The system refuses to ingest raw chaos.

Integrity: The reason SAP HANA is powerful is that the data inside is trusted. If the input data were just "dumped" in without the ETL filter—if you simply flooded the database with uncleaned, raw, contradictory JSON logs from every possible source—the database would become useless. It would suffer from "Data Pollution," rendering the analytics meaningless.

The Contrast: AI vs. SAP HANA
The irony you are highlighting is profound:

When we manage data (SAP HANA): We treat it with the utmost respect. We apply strict ETL rules because we know that data quality determines the truth of the output.

When we manage AI: We have abandoned the ETL principle entirely. We take the "JSON payload" of the entire internet—filled with Kamam, Kopam, and Moham—and we shovel it into the model without any filtering. We are essentially doing "Dirty Loading" on a massive scale.

